{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501336","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501336"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:28:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:28:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1750"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1750","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1750"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.11,0.02,0.02,0.67]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1750"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"32110"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1750","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1750"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1750"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17780"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"493"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3299"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3314"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8070"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36672"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42386"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46852"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"32110","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/32110"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with shortness of breath, a racing heart and dizziness. This all came on suddenly when he was sitting at home eating breakfast. He denies any chest pain. His medical records reveal he has a medical history of hypertension, diabetes, ischaemic heart disease and mild renal impairment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his heart rate is 150/min, blood pressure 112/82mmHg, afebrile and saturating at 97% on room air. He undergoes an ECG, which is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Atrial fibrillation","Supraventricular tachycardia","Sinus tachycardia","STEMI","Atrial flutter"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ECG displays typical \u003Cstrong\u003Eatrial flutter\u003C/strong\u003E. In atrial flutter the atria beat fast due to re-entrant circuit within the right atrium. The ventricular rate depends on the AV conduction, so with an atrial rate of 300/min and a 2:1 block there is a ventricular rate of 150/min, a 3:1 block produces a rate of 100/min and 4:1 a rate of 75/min and so on. If the conduction is 1:1 the patient is often haemodynamically unstable and can sometimes even morph into ventricular fibrillation. The give-away sign that this ECG is atrial flutter rather than another SVT such as atrial fibrillation is the saw tooth pattern most easily seen best in lead II. This is pathognomonic of atrial flutter.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESupraventricular tachycardia (SVT)\u003C/strong\u003E describes a heart arrhythmia that arises from above the Bundle of His fibres. Atrial fibrillation, atrial flutter and sinus tachycardia are all types of SVT among others. An ECG is used to make the diagnosis and demonstrates a narrow complex tachycardia with a rate \u0026gt;100/min. The most common type of SVT is atrioventricular nodal re-entry tachycardia (AVNRT). This has its own typical ECG findings such as hidden P waves, pseudo r and S waves. This is not demonstrated in the ECG above.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtrial fibrillation\u003C/strong\u003E demonstrates an irregularly irregular ECG pattern. There are no p waves, as there is no discernible activity of the atria which are quivering rather than contracting. Only some of the impulses are conducted and hence the ventricular activity is irregular. The ECG above is not consistent with atrial fibrillation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESinus tachycardia\u003C/strong\u003E is a regular heart rhythm that has a rate \u0026gt;100/min for adults. In many situations such as stress and exercise this is a normal response. The ECG displays a normal sinus rhythm with P waves and a QRS following each P wave. This is not displayed by the ECG above.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u0026nbsp;The ECG in this case does not display an ST segment elevation suggestive of a \u003Cstrong\u003ESTEMI\u003C/strong\u003E (ST segment elevation myocardial infarction). A STEMI often presents with crushing chest pain, but they can have atypical presentations, particularly in females and/or diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u0026nbsp;The clinical presentation of most of these conditions is very similar, with palpitations, shortness of breath and dizziness. An ECG is critical to determine the type of arrhythmia occurring. Patients can become haemodynamically unstable and require urgent synchronised DC cardioversion. Otherwise, gentler treatment options are available according to the type of tachyarrhythmia they have.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A saw tooth pattern seen on ECG is highly suggestive of atrial flutter","Atrial fibrillation on ECG has no discernible P waves and an irregularly irregular ventricular rate","A supra-ventricular tachycardia is a type of tachyarrhythmia that originates above the Bundle of His fibres. It has a narrow complex QRS and fast ventricular rate \u003E100 bpm"],"references":["Mitchell L, 2021. Atrial Fibrillation and Atrial Flutter. MSD Manual. Access at: https://www.msdmanuals.com/en-au/home/heart-and-blood-vessel-disorders/abnormal-heart-rhythms/atrial-fibrillation-and-atrial-flutter.","Colucci RA, Silver MJ, Shubrook J. Common types of supraventricular tachycardia: diagnosis and management. Am Fam Physician. 2010 Oct 15;82(8):942-52. PMID: 20949888.","Buttner R \u0026 Burns E, 2021. Atrial Flutter. Life in the Fast Lane. Access at: https://litfl.com/atrial-flutter-ecg-library/.","Cadogan M, 2021. AVNRT for two. Life in the Fast Lane. Access at: https://litfl.com/avnrt-for-two/."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17780"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1750"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19028"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19028","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19028"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0e7090f7-5dfe-40fb-a7e1-df7acbf8f5b0.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0e7090f7-5dfe-40fb-a7e1-df7acbf8f5b0.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":341}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17780","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/17780"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-02-02T17:17:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-10T19:38:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1750"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"32110"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"headin